<paragraph id="4CABFEDF031C1FE84FC597D1878B25FD" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Desert washes, flats, and slopes in coarse, sandy soil.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7B2C148DA63F389E17AC1A53244103FD" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="phenology.">
<paragraph id="FD377FB8C3301BD18E0F5FFA662D0814" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B0D81D7CE18414A1DD2AC79AF9F83AA8" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName id="99BD3A374210172EFEC674FE721AFCE8" authorityName="Still" authorityYear="2014" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="androuxii">
<emphasis id="E712509605D96BE3F31BE6217CC9FF53" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia androuxii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
typically flowers between late-February and early-May but may flower earlier in the season, including in the fall, during years with a summer rain and cool fall temperatures.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="841B3312352AA418CE84610071279C95" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="etymology.">
<paragraph id="5C51EBDBF153A0E8BFDE4B80A6A2DD32" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="402D7BD24CD8D565C7F86319F98B1CE9" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
The species is named for James 
<normalizedToken id="714FEA3AAB100B3CA414663C093136EF" originalValue="André">Andre</normalizedToken>
and Tasha La Doux, two desert botanists and friends that helped point to the problems with desert 
<taxonomicName id="7675F5DF586569AF6CC0F58815B29683" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="84032B17B90E979CBC6E34435C56C8B6" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
identification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="58749CC43334D70A4C9ADE39169F0BC0" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="suggested common name.">
<paragraph id="BCD595C118F438A0678949C8C5B597D1" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Suggested common name.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BF3C58AEF1F3A0FD16F5C53F01B676B3" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Joshua Tree poppy.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0646513603C0B24D7B6DA76A7FD3E59D" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="conservation status.">
<paragraph id="512C3796F0D489BB0A937FB21444F095" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6543B0B70A333CAC9B477AC5E618453B" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">As this is a new taxon it has yet to be considered for conservation status. Due to the limited range and low number of occurrences, the author suggests the California Native Plant Society consider this taxon for listing as a rare plant.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
