<subSubSection id="6A7DCCC53590299A439574C27B5D76E5" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="discussion.">
<paragraph id="0096E202D6BDBCF41DFFCE847F43E819" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7BB97AFFBF17D744A0E1D3D8666180ED" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
This new taxon has a darkened area basipetally located on the stamen filaments (
<figureCitation id="FDD37C879617DCE279D50D801D0E8F2B" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Illustrations of leaves, buds and flowers of Eschscholzia androuxii. A Basal leaf B Cauline leaf C Bud D Petal E Stamens showing diagnostic anthocyanin spot at base of the fused filaments." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10592" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Fig. 1e</figureCitation>
), which are fused at the base. 
<taxonomicName id="B7A52799557A7C043D77EDD062926EEC" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="minutiflora">
<emphasis id="FBB05CE16032A1F2D7CC6BBAE3B9C85F" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia minutiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subsp. 
<emphasis id="388AEA4B827DFEDB126682D031BAA037" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">twisselmannii</emphasis>
also has regularly occurring stamen spots, but only on approximately 70% of specimens examined. No other closely related taxa have these stamen spots. The flower size for this new species is similar to that of the diploid 
<taxonomicName id="2E9B044C58E61230AF6D8DA31786D76C" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="minutiflora">
<emphasis id="57E9EF91348839880AFB8F17696798A6" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia minutiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subsp. 
<emphasis id="1B4782E1A4C9100A42857749CAD59157" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">twisselmannii</emphasis>
but larger than both the hexaploid 
<taxonomicName id="ABD97D22FA5A457F7991E7A98BD8E914" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="minutiflora">
<emphasis id="DA67072A91F57C8008D8F53FBD86CF27" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia minutiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subsp. 
<emphasis id="4E23B3A56330745F32277405CD40CE92" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">minutiflora</emphasis>
and the tetraploid 
<taxonomicName id="73C524657EACE96D27748DF179952135" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="minutiflora">
<emphasis id="ABD3BBC1D64B5DE99E83A2B3590BAE7E" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia minutiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subsp. 
<emphasis id="792A91771B9B6DE7617C47FFD37AEB4C" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">covillei</emphasis>
. The petal size for 
<taxonomicName id="7347ED605FDC6A13BB75AB16EF5196E8" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="minutiflora">
<emphasis id="A48D44A3C3B8ADAB264BE9575063CCE8" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia minutiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subsp. 
<emphasis id="7F167D01BBB5E22629438D12F687EC61" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">covillei</emphasis>
, described in Flora of North America as 6-18 mm long, does overlap with the petal size of 
<taxonomicName id="A4EF8B9A340B23F9BF5D49292F4AFB4A" authorityName="Still" authorityYear="2014" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="androuxii">
<emphasis id="4BBCCAD30877503AAC98CA3AA576AC24" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia androuxii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with petals 10-23 mm long. But more recent morphological study of the genus (
<bibRefCitation id="2AF77EED859747628AE24A2579024EFB" author="Still, SM" journalOrPublisher="Pittonia" pageId="11" pageNumber="56" refId="B5" refString="Still, SM, 2011. Systematic and Taxonomic Studies of Eschscholtzieae (Papaveraceae). PhD thesis, University of California Davis, CA." title="Systematic and Taxonomic Studies of Eschscholtzieae (Papaveraceae). PhD thesis, University of California Davis, CA." year="2011">Still 2011</bibRefCitation>
, Still in preparation) indicates that the petals in 
<taxonomicName id="B201B8C75BB813A97A089BBB91A42F6F" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="minutiflora">
<emphasis id="48B4BC4586483699B828CEE2D02BA0F3" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia minutiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<pageBreakToken id="B5A7F6095F5E28845DA53D518212C695" pageId="4" pageNumber="49" start="start">subsp</pageBreakToken>
. 
<emphasis id="223F496CECD87AF3E59F30AD6BDF9674" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">covillei</emphasis>
range from 4.5-12.5 mm. The reason for this discrepancy may be that some of the larger-flowered 
<taxonomicName id="342E087B324C7772168964126034C9F4" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="4" pageNumber="49" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="minutiflora">
<emphasis id="39D752C817082F3334F4275770E5062D" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">Eschscholzia minutiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subsp. 
<emphasis id="1BC5361FE850B7737EC158134A7FBEE4" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">covillei</emphasis>
specimens are actually the new taxon, 
<taxonomicName id="848918779C4066FDF078DACC2E0E5C0E" authorityName="Still" authorityYear="2014" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="4" pageNumber="49" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="androuxii">
<emphasis id="66366A7ED83C54FF3CA5FBF8822BB4E3" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="49">Eschscholzia androuxii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The Joshua Tree poppy has an overlapping range with several species but is found only in Riverside Co. and the southern part of San Bernardino Co. 
<pageBreakToken id="CC6A9DFA6BC2164185C468E198470069" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" start="start">and</pageBreakToken>
not much further north or south of Joshua Tree National Park. The range does not overlap, and there are more basal leaf ultimate lobes, than with 
<taxonomicName id="AA60442C8CA7BEB61AE2283D2DD20B21" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="minutiflora">
<emphasis id="87847B4C77AD0C765F380B4B6CD69BC4" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Eschscholzia minutiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subsp. 
<emphasis id="B091BBA37D2CBAB45595B3A93D55E204" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">twisselmannii</emphasis>
. The tips of the basal leaf ultimate lobes are more rounded (
<figureCitation id="60021A7E53CF5E821CA0EECDFF996B6B" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Illustrations of leaves, buds and flowers of Eschscholzia androuxii. A Basal leaf B Cauline leaf C Bud D Petal E Stamens showing diagnostic anthocyanin spot at base of the fused filaments." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10592" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
) than what is found in either 
<taxonomicName id="726129AF5F41FD1AF80A80074486E9D1" authorityName="Greene" authorityYear="1885" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="parishii">
<emphasis id="C1B8B7C2542D8C60CD0D7C96C1CAE573" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Eschscholzia parishii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="B99A4FB334D1BFC0AC955762931E207E" authorityName="Still" authorityYear="2014" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="papastillii">
<emphasis id="896C7D086633CCE58451350C032342AA" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Eschscholzia papastillii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="FA437308033883BEAB4CB67EC153C319" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Illustrations of leaves, buds and flowers of Eschscholzia papastillii. A Basal leaf B Cauline leaf C Bud showing widened receptacle D Enlarged receptacle with expanded receptacular rim common in the species E Petal F Stamens lacking the anthocyanin spot at base of the fused filaments common to Eschscholzia androuxii." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10595" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Fig. 4a</figureCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName id="ED3CB8D69E2F9F07DDE86A7539FD6482" authorityName="Still" authorityYear="2014" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="5" pageNumber="50" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="androuxii">
<emphasis id="FCAC393EEC7AE8D5DC6C889F64E62CD2" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Eschscholzia androuxii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has three times the number of cauline leaf ultimate lobes (
<figureCitation id="8462200A534D8CFDBFFB7C0178A71FFE" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Illustrations of leaves, buds and flowers of Eschscholzia androuxii. A Basal leaf B Cauline leaf C Bud D Petal E Stamens showing diagnostic anthocyanin spot at base of the fused filaments." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10592" pageId="5" pageNumber="50">Fig. 1b</figureCitation>
) as these two taxa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
